ce:section.ce:para:
To delve deeper into the fluorescence quenching mechanism of COF-Bpy detecting Cu2+, the fluorescence lifetime, Stern-Volmer equation (details in Supporting 
                              Information
                           ), UV–vis spectra and computational simulations were analyzed. Specifically, after adding Cu2+, the fluorescence lifetime of COF-Bpy decrease from 3.38 ns to 2.83 ns (Fig. 3L), KSV of Stern-Volmer plots increases with temperature (Fig. 3M–Table S4), and UV–vis spectra remain unchanged (Fig. 3N), revealing the occurrence of dynamic quenching (Zu et al., 2017). Subsequently, molecular orbital energies of COF-Bpy before and after Cu2+ coordination were calculated via DMol3 program of Materials Studio (Fig. 3O). Remarkably, the HOMO of COF-Bpy predominantly resides within the p-π conjugation region of the bipyridine, while the LUMO is localized around the phenyl, suggesting internal electrons transfer from the bipyridine to phenyl. After coordinating with Cu2+, electrons transfer from the Cu2+ center (in HOMO) to the vicinity of the phenyl (in LUMO), indicating a typical Metal-to-Ligand Charge Transfer (MLCT) (Gao et al., 2017). Moreover, the energy gap decreases from 1.855 eV to 1.231 eV, suggesting a favorable formation process of complex. Thus, the resulting metal complex exhibits a strong MLCT, which contributes significantly to the observed fluorescence quenching.

Following this, bending and movement of nematodes were assessed after COF-Bpy treatment for 24 h, 48 h and 96 h, compared to the Control and Cu groups. Exposure to high concentration of Cu2+(10 mM) drastically reduces body bending frequency (37.5–66.7% of Control), which may be related to the Cu2+-induced imbalances in the cholinergic system, chaperone function, and oxidative stress (Tamagno et al., 2022). Interestingly, COF-Bpy treatment for 24 h restores body bending frequency to 91.4% of Control, maintaining stability at 95.6% after 48 h (Fig. 5D-5F, Table S9), indicating that COF-Bpy effectively alleviates copper toxicosis in nematodes. Subsequently, locomotor abilities were evaluated via average and maximum speeds of nematode as indices. Exposure to Cu2+ significantly reduces average speed (21.2–26.8% of Control) and maximum speed (32.2–38.1% of Control). However, COF-Bpy treatment for 24 h notably improves average speed (72.9%) and maximum speed (85.8%), locomotor abilities are fully restored after 48 h (average speed of 95.6%, maximum speed of 99.2%). By 96 h, recovery levels decline, suggesting 48 h as the optimal treatment time (Fig. 5G-5L, Table S9). Additionally, nematode crawling trajectories in 50 s were analyzed (Fig. 5M), and dynamic videos (available in Supporting 
                              Information
                           ) confirm enhanced vitality after COF-Bpy treatment. Apparently, exposure to Cu2+ severely inhibited nematode movement, whereas COF-Bpy treatment for 24 h, 48 h and 96 h improved crawling distances, indicating restoration of motility and vitality.
